 slightest, no.  Ignoring for a moment the ethics of <I>charging</I> for the casting of a simple spell, this doesn't make the caster classes any less powerful or the melees any more powerful.  There are other methods of gaining money in the game.  Now if this was the <I>only</I> method for the casters to get money, then it would be drastically game altering.  As it is, it's nothing more than a minor inconvenience to a young caster but a huge convenience to melees at all levels (and casters too, before they get bind).<P>  <BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">quote:</font><HR>What's next to come SoW binders NPC's in every other zone for those that want SoW, but can't find anyone to cast it on them.<HR></BLOCKQUOTE><P>That's a good idea, have a SoW NPC at each city gate.  Druids and shamans would be overjoyed to have less people bothering them for SoW.<P>  <BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">quote:</font><HR>Nexus ports = A neccessity for the game to get to luclin however, there was only to be a couple of these in the innitial design. Before the game came out more where added so that a total of 4 were implimented. More then orignally desired.<HR></BLOCKQUOTE><P>Really?  Where do you get this information from?  How do you know what was originally desired or planned?<P>  <BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">quote:</font><HR>Now once again they added a Nexus port to the Great Divide.<HR></BLOCKQUOTE><P>Will the horrors never cease?!<P>  <BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">quote:</font><HR>Was this stepping on the toes or unbalancing? You bet damn right it was. By doing this a VAST LARGE number Druids and Wizzies were deprived of their income oppurtunity in GD and Thurg by those that wanted to get to Luclin and would have had to get port to a location near a nexus portal.<HR></BLOCKQUOTE><P>How simply tragic!  People will run to a spire, port to Luclin, wait 15 minutes and port down to Great Divide.  Yet these same people will sit for an hour in NFP begging for a teleport to South Ro or WC.  Yes, this is sarcasm but makes the point very well.  People will still seek out druids and wizards to port them to Great Divide (or Greater Faydark, or Toxullia Forest, or North Karana).  This really won't affect them at all.<P>  <BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">quote:</font><HR>I have been in the GD many and many times over and the income potential for a porting class was easily in the range of 100's of plat a day, maybe even a 1,000.<HR></BLOCKQUOTE><P>Oh those poor druids and mages!  How will they ever survive without that extra 1Kpp a day?!  Quick, I think we should all start donating to the "Save a Druid Relief Fund".<P>  <BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">quote:</font><HR>This definately stepped on a CLASS definning skill that only 2 have (druids/wizzies) and yet most don't complain.<HR></BLOCKQUOTE><P>I suspect from your whining you have no clue how the portals work.  They port down to Norrath and a moment later the portals activate on Norrath transporting people to the Nexus.  It's impossible to use the system for quick porting, there will be a quarter hour wait if you want to "abuse" the portal system.<P>  <BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">quote:</font><HR>This also hurt standard ports as well, because many now that wish not to donate for ports to DL (kunark) can simply take the Nexus up and back down to Kunark.<HR></BLOCKQUOTE><P>With a 15 minute wait in the process.  Assuming the person is willing to run to the nearest portal in the first place, which isn't likely considering they won't even run from NFP to South Ro or WC.<P>  <BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">quote:</font><HR>Another fact all returning ports from luclin back to Norrath are 5 minutes after you arrive, so this way you would not have to wait for another 15 minutes.<HR></BLOCKQUOTE><P>Your fact is, in fact, incorrect.<P>  <BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, 