This is hilarious, I love it!  <IMG SRC="biggrin.gif" border="0"><P>Your arguements, while correct, aren't as strong as you think.<P> <BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">quote:</font><HR> Fear Immunity = making pets safer in high level dungeons? Does this not unbalance the tanking class to where they are more reliable then a pet? Afterall, again you argue RISK with everything. It's a risk I take to go in dungeons without SoW, correct? So how is that Risk different then the risk of a Caster taking his pet into zones where FEAR is a deffinate possibilty? <HR></BLOCKQUOTE><P>Very rarely will we have to deal with a fearing mob pre 50.  Post 50 tanks have such a high mr (well the good tanks do anyway)that they are virtually unfearable.  Nevermind the fact that they are sooooo much better tanks then our pets.  More hitpoints, more damage, far more ac, and in the case of warriors, defensive discipline.  No way will a pet ever replace a tank on a raid, and thats the only time when this issue becomes a point of concern.<P>Your comparison of sow with haveing our pets feared isn't a very fair one.  While I will have to admit that you could look at it that way, I will explain the whole situation.  <P>First off if you go into a dungeon without sow, you are hardly helpless.  You still have that monster of a pet, and you still have flash of light.<P>Now consider that in order for us to be fighting one of these fearing mobs we would have to be on a raid (you wouldn't be stupid enough to try and solo a mob who will fear your pet would you?).  On a raid our escape mechanisms aren't necessary, as we will either die, or be evacced.  Now keeping that in mind, also keep in mind the percentage of our usefullnes our pet is.  Our pet is at least 60% of our class, and I would be willing to bet more like 70%.  If you take away our pet (not because it got feared but because your raid leader won't allow you to because it will get feared) then you have a class that's operating at 30% efficiency.  Now why would anyone want a class who's sole purpose is savegery on MA and maybe spiritual purity (I believe it has some stacking issues).  Oh and of course we can't forget our bard level damage (some people say knights, but if the knights in my guild are any indication, we are bard level.  Those big 2 handers with a large dose of haste are just plain nasty.<P>So you are, in essence, comparing loseing a tooth to loseing a limb.  While your arguement does hold ground, it is still very very weak.<P> <BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">quote:</font><HR> Soul Binders = Was a direct stepping on toes of every binding class. You talk about hide/sneak/FD/ID stepping on the toes of those classes that have those skill or abilites. However by adding soul binders you have taken away from those classes that sometimes relay on that for income durring off times when not adventuring. Granted a high level binder could care less about 10pp donation for a bid. BUT a much lower level newbie just starting the game that is so maybe 8th level has been deprived of that possiblity. And you don't call this unbalancing? What's next to come SoW binders NPC's in every other zone for those that want SoW, but can't find anyone to cast it on them.  <HR></BLOCKQUOTE><P>First I would like to say I would like to meet any bind class who is truly mad about this (excluding you I suppose).<P>Secondly comparing binding to fd/id/sneak/hide is another example of comparing loseing a tooth to loeing a limb.  You know what the bind classes lost with the addition of soul binders?  The ability to make a quick buck around level 14.  You know what a monk would lose if someone else got fd?  Basically the reason why most sane groups get the monk in the first place.  Very few experienced players are going to say, "let's get that monk, they do great damage."  That just doesn't make a lot of sense when there are rogues out there doing well more then a monk.<P>As for your sow binders idea, I love it.  Think it's one of the best ideas I have ever heard.  The sowless classes can always get a sow when they need one, and the classes who can sow will no longer be irritated by people who walk up to them and say, "sow plz."  I'm willing to bet the overall population of druids, shamans, rangers, and beastlords would be quite happy.  I know every time someone walks up to me and asks for sow I get a little irritated, always do it though, it's just mana.  On a side note I have yet to be payed for sow, so it's not like I am loseing money on the deal.  And it's not like a group would put up with the puller makeing a long trip (long being figurative for 5 to 10 minutes) every time he needs sow.  They would get a sow class just to save themselves the time and trouble.<P>(I didn't comment on ID, sneak, and hide because I am not familiar with a rogue, or how important those abilites are.  I, unlike certain other people, prefer not to comment on something I know nothing about.)<P> <BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">quote:</font><HR> Nexus ports = A neccessity for the game to get to luclin however, there was only to be a couple of these in the innitial design. Before the game came out more where added so that a total of 4 were implimented. More then orignally desired. Now once again they added a Nexus port to the Great Divide. Was this stepping on the toes or unbalancing? You bet damn right it was. By doing this a VAST LARGE number Druids and Wizzies were deprived of their income oppurtunity in GD and Thurg by those that wanted to get to Luclin and would have had to get port to a location near a nexus portal. I have been in the GD many and many times over and the income potential for a porting class was easily in the range of 100's of plat a day, maybe even a 1,000. This definately stepped on a CLASS definning skill that only 2 have (druids/wizzies) and yet most don't complain.  <HR></BLOCKQUOTE><P>Class defining skill?  To my knowledge, a druid doesn't have a class defining skill, unless you count being incredibly versatile.  Last time I checked the wizards class defining skill was massive nukes.  But enough of that discussion, i'll get to the heart of the matter.<P>First off on my server I see no less of a want for ports.  People get ports to save them time.  A lot of people don't care if that time is 5 minutes or an hour.  Afterall, it isn't uncommon to see people asking for ports to a zone one zone away.  I have seen people in oasis ask for a port south ro, and I have seen people in east commnlands ask for a port to west commonlands.  All the nexus did was make it so that people don't have to wait 30 minutes for a port.  I can run and sit at the spires, all the while yelling for a port.  If I get one, great!  If not I at least have an idea of how long it will take me to get somewhere.  I am proactive.  If I need a port, I yell for one as I walk to the place I am trying to get to.  If my server is any indication I am in the one percentile of people who think that way.  I have seen people sit in DL shouting for a port to bb for an hour, when they could have been there already if they had taken the boat.<P>Also, why do you think wizards are almost always anon?  Do you believe that they do this just to be mysterious?  They do it to not be bothered for ports.  I have a wizard friend who has been anon for well over 6 months.  I would say the same for druids, but they have a couple other reasons, asides from porting, to go anon.<P>And let's not forget you have to have Luclin to use the spires.  While they claim to have sold 800,000 copies of Luclin, I don't see the upswing in population to support this.  My server seems even less populated now, and among the people I talk to a lot of people have quit because of how disappointing Luclin was.<P>And maybe it's just a coincidence, but everytime I use the nexus to go to the moon, when I arrive, it's 5 minutes to Velious ports.  Now if this isn't a coincidence (and I have used the nexus a good deal, I usually don't carry cash with me for ports, and I am almost never in a hurry)  Then that means my minimum wait to get to anywhere not Velious is 21 minutes.<P>I of course could be wrong, if anyone (excluding rudeson) cares to correct me feel free.<P>Oh, and of course, let's not forget that only 3 of the nexus ports are commonly used.  I have, in my entire year of playing this game, seen only 1 person looking for a port to Toxx, and 5 to the karanas.  Almost all ports are to DL (a nexus spire), GFAY (A nexus drop spire) GD (a nexus drop) and, of course, the most common one of all, WC (note that it is not a nexus drop).  Now, while haveing the toxx drop and karana drop are handy when you need them, I have net to wander past one of their pads in Nexus and seen someone there waiting to go down.  I don't doubt that it happens, but it certainly isn't like the Kunark pad, which is always crowded.<P>So yes, I suppose the nexus does cut into port profits, does it cut into it in any major way?  Maybe, I can't even begin to ponder the economics of this game, as I find them to be screwed up severely.  But since there is ALWAYS someone in DL or WC that needs a port, I don't think it's a big problem to those druids who are playing taxi to make some money.<P> <BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">quote:</font><HR> BTW with the release of vendor bought horses, wasn't that a direct UNBALANCING of classes giving virtually all Class the ability of Jboots/SoW/or faster speeds? It sure looks that way to me. What is next? I know a Vendor that teaches you the art of Body Control and Meditation. You pay him 50K in plat and he teaches you to Feign Death.. hahahahaha or to meditate at the same rate as C2... hahahahaha  <HR></BLOCKQUOTE><P>First off have you ever heard of Tboots?  Probably not.  Full name is travelors boots.  Some gnome sells them in Sol A for 5500pp and they give close to jboot speed.  Oh and of course lets not forget the basic AA XP ability to make you run almost as fast as jboots.<P>Again correct me if I am wrong, but can horses be used indoors?  I don't think they can...could be wrong though.  Not like I own one, nor will I ever own one.  If I ever have the 100k to buy a worthwhile horse (8k for a barely faster then running speed horse?  I think not..)I will finally make that twink gnome warrior with full cobalt.<P>And of course again, sow is not a class defining ability.  If it was, don't you think the sow classes would be highly agitated at bards, seeing as how bards easily outrun sow?<P>And as for the ability to buy c2...well there's a c3 (koadil's endless intellect)out now so   <IMG SRC="tongue.gif" border="0">
